    <section id="sect-00001">
      <title>Systems of Measurement</title>
      <section id="sect-00002">
        <title>International Systems of Units</title>
        <para id="para-00001">The International System of Units (SI) is an international standard of measurement that is also known as the metric system. The SI system is made up of 7 base units that define 22 units with special names and symbols. For the purpose of this section, only the metric system used for dosage calculation will be covered.
        </para>
      </section>
        <section id="sect-00003">
          <title>Metric System</title>
          <para id="para-00002">Three types of metric measures are commonly used: length, volume, and weight. This section covers volume and weight.</para>
          <para id="para-00003">Volume measures a liquid and is commonly used in dosage calculation when measuring liquid drugs, in the reconstitution of drugs, or with intravenous therapy. The metric system defines volume in units of liters.</para>
          <para id="para-00004">Weight measures mass and is commonly used in dosage calculation when a particular drug is administered based on the patient’s weight. The metric system defines weight in units of grams.</para>
          <para id="para-00005">It is important to understand the units can be smaller or larger in relation to their metric measure (<link target-id="table_02_01"/>).
            <list list-type="bulleted" id="list-00001">
              <item>Kilo is a larger unit of measurement and equals 1000.</item>
              <item>Milli is a smaller unit of measurement and equals 1/1000.</item>
              <item>Micro is also a smaller measurement and equals 1/1,000,000.</item>
            </list>
          </para>

