      <section id="sect-00012">
        <title>Body Surface Area (BSA) Method</title>
        <para id="para-00016">The body surface area (BSA) method allows dosage calculation for individualization. This method is commonly seen with medications that have a narrow therapeutic index, that are being adjusted due to the individual’s ability to metabolize the drug, chemotherapeutic agents, and/or that are used with pediatric and burn patients. BSA is calculated using the square root calculation as determined by the patient’s height and weight.
        </para>
      </section>
  </section>
  <section id="sect-00013">
    <title>Rounding Rules</title>
    <para id="para-00017">Nurses must know when and how to round. Caplets and tablets can be rounded to the nearest half tablet if they are scored. Some are scored in fourths and can be rounded accordingly. Caplets and tablets that are controlled release, extended release, sustained release, or are enteric coated should not be split or crushed. Capsules are rounded to the nearest whole number because these cannot be divided. Liquid drugs are rounded to the nearest tenth. If you are calculating a liquid medication for drops, then it is to be rounded to the nearest whole number because you cannot administer a partial drop.
    </para>
<para id="para-00018">Next, rounding is determined by how many places from the decimal point are appropriate. If a number to the right of the decimal point needs to be rounded and it is 4 or less, then it is rounded down. For example, if the number is 1.231 and you are rounding to the nearest tenth, the number would be rounded 1.2. If a number to the right of the decimal point is 5 or greater, then it should be rounded up. For example, if the number is 1.251 and you are rounding to the nearest tenth, the number would be rounded to 1.3.
</para>
</section>
